you do a bang-up job.

85
00:05:30,864 --> 00:05:32,698
When you're here.

86
00:05:32,700 --> 00:05:35,334
Hence my dilemma.

87
00:05:35,336 --> 00:05:37,402
How to let you go

88
00:05:37,404 --> 00:05:40,372
without being the bad guy.

89
00:05:40,374 --> 00:05:44,076
Or how to let you stay
without appearing weak.

90
00:05:44,078 --> 00:05:45,444
Come again, sir?

91
00:05:45,446 --> 00:05:49,047
I have this little
pet project of mine.

92
00:05:49,049 --> 00:05:51,116
More of a passion, really.

93
00:05:51,118 --> 00:05:53,952
I stumbled on this
about five years ago

94
00:05:53,954 --> 00:05:56,355
when I took over
the chief's job.

95
00:05:58,024 --> 00:05:59,958
Arizona, 1892.

96
00:05:59,960 --> 00:06:01,893
Bank robbery gone wrong.

97
00:06:01,895 --> 00:06:04,363
Six people dead.

98
00:06:04,365 --> 00:06:06,431
They called it
the mid-day massacre.

99
00:06:06,433 --> 00:06:09,401
September 23rd, 1892.

100
00:06:09,403 --> 00:06:12,704
Four men, led by
an ill-tempered outlaw

101
00:06:12,706 --> 00:06:15,073
named levi harden,
walked into a bank.

102
00:06:15,075 --> 00:06:18,977
In the small boom-town
of young country, Arizona.

103
00:06:18,979 --> 00:06:21,446
When the smoke cleared,
six people were dead,

104
00:06:21,448 --> 00:06:23,448
including
a five-year-old girl.

105
00:06:23,450 --> 00:06:24,783
Traveling photographer

106
00:06:24,785 --> 00:06:27,519
happened to be passing
through town that day.

107
00:06:29,723 --> 00:06:33,024
Sheldon, the one that
started the gazette.

108
00:06:33,026 --> 00:06:35,127
That's right, and what
was supposed to be

109
00:06:35,129 --> 00:06:37,496
a series
of rudimentary shots

110
00:06:37,498 --> 00:06:39,464
to test a camera
he'd invented

111
00:06:39,466 --> 00:06:41,500
ended up capturing
one of the only

112
00:06:41,502 --> 00:06:43,902
live bank robberies
ever caught on film.

113
00:06:43,904 --> 00:06:45,170
[Gunshots]
Run!

114
00:06:45,172 --> 00:06:47,005
No, men, stand down!
Stand down!

115
00:06:47,007 --> 00:06:48,774
Don't shoot! Don't shoot!

116
00:06:48,776 --> 00:06:50,942
Don't you--
I'll fucking kill her!

117
00:06:50,944 --> 00:06:52,611
Hey, I'll kill her, Duke!

118
00:06:52,613 --> 00:06:54,079
Hardin, don't you hurt her!

119
00:06:54,081 --> 00:06:55,514
I know you don't want that.

120
00:06:55,516 --> 00:06:58,150
[Hammer clicks]

121
00:06:58,152 --> 00:06:59,785
Don't!

122
00:06:59,787 --> 00:07:01,686
[Woman screams]

123
00:07:08,027 --> 00:07:10,595
No!

124
00:07:15,168 --> 00:07:16,868
[Man grunts]

125
00:07:20,873 --> 00:07:22,507
Come on!

126
00:07:23,509 --> 00:07:25,610
Hee-Yah! Hyah!

127
00:07:30,650 --> 00:07:32,918
It gained
national attention,

128
00:07:32,920 --> 00:07:35,520
what with the vicious
nature of the crime

129
00:07:35,522 --> 00:07:39,491
and the high-profiled
individuals involved.

130
00:07:39,493 --> 00:07:40,859
One in particular,

131
00:07:40,861 --> 00:07:44,029
a well-respected
U.S. marshal

132
00:07:44,031 --> 00:07:46,898
named Duke Donovan.

133
00:07:46,900 --> 00:07:49,868
That him?

134
00:07:49,870 --> 00:07:51,636
Mm-hmm.

135
00:07:51,638 --> 00:07:55,207
Some say he was
the ringleader.

136
00:07:55,209 --> 00:07:57,042
So the man people
were supposed to trust

137
00:07:57,044 --> 00:07:59,044
ended up betraying them.

138
00:07:59,046 --> 00:08:00,612
Doesn't end there.

139
00:08:00,614 --> 00:08:01,880
Donovan and hardin

140
00:08:01,882 --> 00:08:04,716
escaped free
and clear that day.

141
00:08:04,718 --> 00:08:08,053
But a posse
caught up to them later.

142
00:08:21,234 --> 00:08:23,702
This one's alive.

143
00:08:23,704 --> 00:08:26,238
So hardin double-crossed
Donovan and took the money.

144
00:08:26,240 --> 00:08:30,008
On the contrary, it's all
right there with Donovan.

145
00:08:30,010 --> 00:08:32,878
Donovan claimed that
he was trying to stop them,

146
00:08:32,880 --> 00:08:35,280
but hardin was
holding a woman hostage

147
00:08:35,282 --> 00:08:36,948
outside of town.

148
00:08:36,950 --> 00:08:38,583
He said
he was gonna kill her

149
00:08:38,585 --> 00:08:40,919
if Donovan didn't
aid in the robbery.

150
00:08:40,921 --> 00:08:43,288
So Donovan said
he went along with it,

151
00:08:43,290 --> 00:08:44,789
until the last second.

152
00:08:44,791 --> 00:08:48,126
There was no sign
of a mysterious woman.

153
00:08:48,128 --> 00:08:49,961
And hardin?
Donovan claimed

154
00:08:49,963 --> 00:08:53,732
he shot him in the head
before he blacked out.

155
00:08:53,734 --> 00:08:56,268
Never found the body.

156
00:08:56,270 --> 00:08:57,702
Well, what happened next?

157
00:08:57,704 --> 00:08:59,771
I don't know
if it was his 20 years

158
00:08:59,773 --> 00:09:01,106
of service to the law,

159
00:09:01,108 --> 00:09:02,741
or the fact
that Donovan claimed

160
00:09:02,743 --> 00:09:05,043
he never fired a shot
during the robbery,

161
00:09:05,045 --> 00:09:07,145
but something put doubts

162
00:09:07,147 --> 00:09:08,647
in the minds of the jury.

163
00:09:08,649 --> 00:09:11,082
That's a hangin' offense,

164
00:09:11,084 --> 00:09:12,684
but they sentenced him

165
00:09:12,686 --> 00:09:15,153
to life in the yuma
territorial prison.

166
00:09:15,155 --> 00:09:17,322
He lasted there six weeks

167
00:09:17,324 --> 00:09:19,724
before escaping.

168
00:09:19,726 --> 00:09:22,127
He was killed two days later

169
00:09:22,129 --> 00:09:23,762
by a young deputy.

170
00:09:23,764 --> 00:09:24,963
Sounds like quite a story.

171
00:09:24,965 --> 00:09:26,331
Oh, it is.
I had to uncover

172
00:09:26,333 --> 00:09:29,668
a lot of rocks
to find this much.

173
00:09:29,670 --> 00:09:31,336
But what do you think?

174
00:09:31,338 --> 00:09:34,005
I'm not sure.

175
00:09:34,007 --> 00:09:37,008
But I'm gonna let you
help me form that opinion.

176
00:09:37,010 --> 00:09:39,144
How's that?
By getting an interview

177
00:09:39,146 --> 00:09:40,645
with the last man alive

178
00:09:40,647 --> 00:09:41,880
who knows
what really happened.

179
00:09:41,882 --> 00:09:44,783
His name
is Seymour redfield.

180
00:09:44,785 --> 00:09:46,751
Some people think
his real name

181
00:09:46,753 --> 00:09:48,653
is tom Sullivan.

182
00:09:48,655 --> 00:09:52,223
The young deputy that
killed Donovan that day.

183
00:09:52,225 --> 00:09:55,627
When Sullivan brought
Donovan's body back to town,

184
00:09:55,629 --> 00:09:58,663
he disappeared.
Was never heard from again.

185
00:09:58,665 --> 00:10:00,799
Why don't you just
talk to this man?

186
00:10:00,801 --> 00:10:02,200
Well...

187
00:10:02,202 --> 00:10:04,636
Let's just say
we don't see eye to eye

188
00:10:04,638 --> 00:10:05,870
and leave it at that.

189
00:10:05,872 --> 00:10:08,940
Only interview I never got.

190
00:10:08,942 --> 00:10:10,809
Well, what makes you think
he'll wanna talk to me?

191
00:10:10,811 --> 00:10:13,745
Because you have
more motivation than I do.

192
00:10:13,747 --> 00:10:16,114
Your job's on the line.

193
00:10:16,116 --> 00:10:19,351
Get the story.

194
00:10:19,353 --> 00:10:20,885
Or...

195
00:11:07,299 --> 00:11:09,167
Hello?

196
00:11:12,271 --> 00:11:14,005
Hello?

197
00:11:18,411 --> 00:11:20,945
Hello? Mr. redfield?

198
00:11:34,960 --> 00:11:37,262
Jeez.

199
00:11:48,741 --> 00:11:51,943
That's a .45 long colt.

200
00:11:59,185 --> 00:12:00,785
Its many admirers

201
00:12:00,787 --> 00:12:04,422
referred to it
as the peacemaker.

202
00:12:04,424 --> 00:12:06,191
Mr. redfield?

203
00:12:06,193 --> 00:12:09,027
Depends on who's asking.

204
00:12:09,029 --> 00:12:10,929
I'm Jesse helms,
from the gazette.

205
00:12:10,931 --> 00:12:12,030
[Groans]

206
00:12:12,032 --> 00:12:14,999
I was hoping
I could talk to you.

207
00:12:17,803 --> 00:12:21,005
I'd've thought you people'd
take the hint by now.

208
00:12:25,478 --> 00:12:28,179
Um, I didn't mean
to intrude, sir.

209
00:12:28,181 --> 00:12:30,081
Knocked on the door,
and it fell open.

210
00:12:30,083 --> 00:12:33,284
You know, I could've blown
your goddamn head off.

211
00:12:33,286 --> 00:12:36,254
And I'd've been
well within my rights.

212
00:12:38,257 --> 00:12:41,092
But, since I just
saved your life,

213
00:12:41,094 --> 00:12:44,229
why don't you have
a drink with me?

214
00:12:44,231 --> 00:12:46,231
Uh, no-- no thank you, sir.

215
00:12:46,233 --> 00:12:47,766
I'm on the clock.

216
00:12:47,768 --> 00:12:49,234
Whose clock?

217
00:12:49,236 --> 00:12:52,170
Not my clock.

218
00:12:52,172 --> 00:12:54,139
Well, in that case,

219
00:12:54,141 --> 00:12:56,307
a small one, sir.

220
00:13:03,149 --> 00:13:04,849
Why don't you
rest your butt?

221
00:13:04,851 --> 00:13:08,086
Make yourself comfortable.

222
00:13:08,088 --> 00:13:10,021
Thank you, sir.

223
00:13:12,858 --> 00:13:15,126
You know, my, uh...
[Redfield sighs]

224
00:13:15,128 --> 00:13:18,229
Chief said that you didn't
like to talk too much.

225
00:13:18,231 --> 00:13:22,233
Your chief?
You mean Morgan heinz?

226
00:13:22,235 --> 00:13:24,068
Well, pay no attention
to Morgan heinz.

227
00:13:24,070 --> 00:13:27,972
He's nothing but
a damned old blowhard.

228
00:13:27,974 --> 00:13:31,009
Only thing he's interested in

229
00:13:31,011 --> 00:13:33,211
is a good scandal
so as he can sell

230
00:13:33,213 --> 00:13:36,314
more sheets of that
rag he puts out.

231
00:13:39,819 --> 00:13:41,986
Heinz said that
if I didn't talk to you,

232
00:13:41,988 --> 00:13:44,122
then I'd be out of a job.

233
00:13:44,124 --> 00:13:47,058
Oh, well, that's too bad.

234
00:13:47,060 --> 00:13:49,894
However, I hear the pig farm

235
00:13:49,896 --> 00:13:52,397
down the road is hiring.

236
00:13:55,267 --> 00:13:57,268
You know, sir,
I don't wanna waste

237
00:13:57,270 --> 00:14:00,839
any more of your time.

238
00:14:00,841 --> 00:14:04,576
I'll see myself out.

239
00:14:04,578 --> 00:14:07,912
[Hammer clicks]

240
00:14:14,587 --> 00:14:17,255
I inherited this gun

241
00:14:17,257 --> 00:14:18,923
from Duke Donovan.

242
00:14:18,925 --> 00:14:21,926
The day he died.

243
00:14:21,928 --> 00:14:25,330
Marshal Duke Donovan?

244
00:14:25,332 --> 00:14:27,532
The very one.

245
00:14:27,534 --> 00:14:31,236
Was that the gun
he used in the robbery?

246
00:14:31,238 --> 00:14:33,504
Is that why heinz
sent you here?

247
00:14:33,506 --> 00:14:35,640
Talk about Duke Donovan?

248
00:14:35,642 --> 00:14:38,543
Well, yes, sir. It is.

249
00:14:38,545 --> 00:14:40,278
Well...

250
00:14:40,280 --> 00:14:44,082
I suppose if you're
looking for the truth,

251
00:14:44,084 --> 00:14:48,186
that's where it all began.

252
00:14:48,188 --> 00:14:49,654
With Donovan.

253
00:14:49,656 --> 00:14:51,623
By 1892,

254
00:14:51,625 --> 00:14:53,958
some say the legend
of Duke Donovan

255
00:14:53,960 --> 00:14:57,295
had begun
to eclipse the man.

256
00:15:09,508 --> 00:15:11,309
He never had any children.

257
00:15:11,311 --> 00:15:13,444
On account of their
getting married

258
00:15:13,446 --> 00:15:15,113
later in life.

259
00:15:15,115 --> 00:15:18,416
Just a wife
he loved fiercely.

260
00:15:18,418 --> 00:15:22,186
♪ They say that
every name is written down ♪

261
00:15:22,188 --> 00:15:24,455
But their passion
for each other

262
00:15:24,457 --> 00:15:26,157
more than made up for it.

263
00:15:26,159 --> 00:15:29,961
♪ One day
our time will come ♪

264
00:15:29,963 --> 00:15:31,663
Their love was constant.

265
00:15:31,665 --> 00:15:33,665
♪ And every one of us

266
00:15:33,667 --> 00:15:36,301
♪ will stand alone

267
00:15:38,370 --> 00:15:40,204
♪ to account for
what we've done ♪

268
00:15:40,206 --> 00:15:41,572
Through thick and thin,

269
00:15:41,574 --> 00:15:45,009
she stood by him.

270
00:15:45,011 --> 00:15:47,545
Has the jury reached
their verdict?

271
00:15:47,547 --> 00:15:49,580
We have, your honor.

